1
00:00:01,744 --> 00:00:03,719
Instructor: The final thing that we want to work on

2
00:00:03,719 --> 00:00:06,060
is when we hit the Update Role

3
00:00:06,060 --> 00:00:07,683
it should update the role.

4
00:00:08,520 --> 00:00:13,200
So let me switch back here and copy the RoleManagement.

5
00:00:13,200 --> 00:00:16,020
Paste that one more time here,

6
00:00:16,020 --> 00:00:19,983
remove everything, and this will be HttpPost.

7
00:00:21,600 --> 00:00:23,910
What we will be getting here

8
00:00:23,910 --> 00:00:26,820
will be the RoleManagementVM model

9
00:00:26,820 --> 00:00:30,300
because we did not bind that property.

10
00:00:30,300 --> 00:00:32,674
In order to get the RoleId

11
00:00:32,674 --> 00:00:35,903
we will have to go to roleManagementVM model

12
00:00:35,903 --> 00:00:39,320
.ApplicationUser.Id, and then the RoleID.

13
00:00:41,489 --> 00:00:44,550
Now this RoleID is the current role.

14
00:00:44,550 --> 00:00:47,880
So let me retrieve the oldRole from the database,

15
00:00:47,880 --> 00:00:50,253
that way we know what is the old role.

16
00:00:51,360 --> 00:00:55,350
We will check here if not, and if the current role

17
00:00:55,350 --> 00:00:58,147
which is inside roleManagementVM model

18
00:00:58,147 --> 00:01:02,820
.ApplicationUser.Role is not equal to oldRole,

19
00:01:02,820 --> 00:01:04,923
that means a role was updated.

20
00:01:06,450 --> 00:01:08,580
Now, when we have to update anything,

21
00:01:08,580 --> 00:01:12,420
let me retrieve the application user from the database,

22
00:01:12,420 --> 00:01:15,060
and then I will check one thing.

23
00:01:15,060 --> 00:01:18,876
If roleManagement.ApplicationUser.Role

24
00:01:18,876 --> 00:01:20,313
== SD.Role_Company,

25
00:01:22,380 --> 00:01:25,110
that means along with assigning the role,

26
00:01:25,110 --> 00:01:29,103
we also have to assign company to that application user.

27
00:01:29,940 --> 00:01:33,556
So we can set applicationUser.CompanyId

28
00:01:33,556 --> 00:01:37,395
= roleManagementVM model

29
00:01:37,395 --> 00:01:39,645
.ApplicationUser.CompanyId.

30
00:01:42,420 --> 00:01:45,600
Then if the oldRole was a company role,

31
00:01:45,600 --> 00:01:48,780
then we have to remove that CompanyId.

32
00:01:48,780 --> 00:01:53,760
So ApplicationUser.CompanyId will be null.

33
00:01:53,760 --> 00:01:56,280
So that is everything that we have to update

34
00:01:56,280 --> 00:02:00,033
with applicationUser, so let me save the changes.

35
00:02:01,110 --> 00:02:03,780
Now finally, we have to remove the old role

36
00:02:03,780 --> 00:02:06,663
and assign the new role to our user.

37
00:02:07,590 --> 00:02:11,613
For that we have helper method inside UserManager.

38
00:02:12,840 --> 00:02:16,353
Let me retrieve that using dependency injection.

39
00:02:18,510 --> 00:02:21,090
Perfect, now if we go down,

40
00:02:21,090 --> 00:02:23,111
we need to remove the oldRole.

41
00:02:23,111 --> 00:02:26,883
So _userManager.RemoveRoleAsync,

42
00:02:28,230 --> 00:02:31,050
and we have to pass the user object,

43
00:02:31,050 --> 00:02:33,150
which is applicationUser, and the oldRole,

44
00:02:34,230 --> 00:02:38,550
we have to provide that, which is in oldRole.

45
00:02:38,550 --> 00:02:40,140
It is an Async method,

46
00:02:40,140 --> 00:02:43,803
so we will call GetAwaiter.GetResult.

47
00:02:45,570 --> 00:02:48,480
Copy that, paste it one more time.

48
00:02:48,480 --> 00:02:52,590
Once we remove the oldRole, we have to AddToRoleAsync

49
00:02:53,460 --> 00:02:56,010
and we have to add the new role

50
00:02:56,010 --> 00:02:59,917
that is inside VM model .ApplicationUser.Role.

51
00:03:03,060 --> 00:03:08,060
Finally, let me Redirect to the "Index" action, and perfect.

52
00:03:08,460 --> 00:03:10,920
With that, let me go back,

53
00:03:10,920 --> 00:03:14,160
and we will have to restart the application

54
00:03:14,160 --> 00:03:16,443
to test everything that we have.

55
00:03:18,870 --> 00:03:22,833
Perfect, let me log in as an admin here.

56
00:03:24,570 --> 00:03:27,270
And we go to Manage User,

57
00:03:27,270 --> 00:03:29,220
we have a company account.

58
00:03:29,220 --> 00:03:32,043
Let me go back in the database,

59
00:03:33,060 --> 00:03:38,060
and if I examine that email is company@gmail, where is that?

60
00:03:39,090 --> 00:03:43,290
Right here, it should have a CompanyId.

61
00:03:43,290 --> 00:03:47,790
If I change that role to be Employee, Update Role,

62
00:03:47,790 --> 00:03:49,470
perfect, that is done.

63
00:03:49,470 --> 00:03:54,470
And if I execute the CompanyId should be gone, perfect.

64
00:03:55,680 --> 00:03:59,700
If I edit that again to be a company,

65
00:03:59,700 --> 00:04:04,263
change that, let me execute here,

66
00:04:05,910 --> 00:04:09,870
and perfect, the CompanyId is getting assigned

67
00:04:09,870 --> 00:04:13,560
and the role is also back to Company.

68
00:04:13,560 --> 00:04:15,810
So with that, you can see how easy it is

69
00:04:15,810 --> 00:04:20,493
to manage roles dynamically from the portal in .NET Core.

